\begin_layout Standard
We present the results of a radial velocity (RV) survey of 14 brown dwarfs
 (BDs) and very low-mass (VLM) stars in the Upper Scorpius OB association
 (UScoOB) and 3 BD candidates in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
Ophiuchi dark cloud core.
 We obtained high-resolution echelle spectra at the VLT using Ultraviolet
 and Visual Echelle Spectrograph (UVES) at two different epochs for each
 object, and measured the shifts in their RVs to identify candidates for
 binary/multiple systems in the sample.
 The average time separation of the RV measurements is 21.6\InsetSpace ~
d, and our survey
 is sensitive to the binaries with separation 
\begin_inset Formula $<0.1$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
au.
 We found 4 out of 17 objects (or 
\begin_inset Formula $24_{-13}^{+16}$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
per\InsetSpace ~
cent by fraction) show a significant RV change in 4--33\InsetSpace ~
d time scale,
 and are considered as binary/multiple `candidates.' We found no double-lined
 spectroscopic binaries in our sample, based on the shape of cross-correlation
 curves.
 The RV dispersion of the objects in UScoOB is found to be very similar
 to that of the BD and VLM stars in Chamaeleon\InsetSpace ~
I (Cha\InsetSpace ~
).
 We also found the distribution of the mean rotational velocities (
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i$
\end_inset

) of the UScoOB objects is similar to that of the Cha\InsetSpace ~
I, but the dispersion
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i$
\end_inset

 is much larger than that of the Cha\InsetSpace ~
I objects.
\end_layout

