\begin_layout Standard
The separation distribution of BD/VLM binaries is critical to understanding
 their origin.
 There are two main models for the formation of BDs and VLM stars: first,
 they have low masses because they form in low-mass, dense molecular cloud
 cores (e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citealt{padoan:2002}
\end_layout

\end_inset

); second, BD/VLM objects have low masses because they are ejected from
 the dense core in which they form via dynamical interactions in multiple
 system, cutting off their accretion before they have reached stellar masses
 (
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citealt{reipurth:2001}
\end_layout

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citealt*{bate:2002}
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 Alternatively, there is a third model in which a free-floating BD or planetary-
mass object can be formed in the process of the photo-evaporation (e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citealt{mccaughrean:2002}
\end_layout

\end_inset

;\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citealt{whitworth:2004}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) with the outer layers of a pre-stellar core (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.2\,\mathrm{M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

) removed by the strong radiation pressure from the nearby massive OB stars
 before the accretion onto the protostar at core centre occurs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the dynamical interaction involved in the second model, BD/VLM binaries
 that survive are generally expected to have small separations.
 In the first model, wider binaries may be expected to be more common.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet*{bate:2002b}
\end_layout

\end_inset

