\begin_layout Standard
The rotational velocities of the objects were determined by measuring the
 widths of the cross correlation functions of the target spectra against
 a template spectrum from an object which is known to have a very small
 rotational velocity.
 The line broadening of the targets is assumed to be dominated by rotational
 broadening.
 As in the cases for the radial velocity measurements, LHS\InsetSpace ~
49 is chosen as
 the template.
 Using its rotational period (
\begin_inset Formula $P\approx83\,\mathrm{d}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citealt{benedict:1998}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) and radius (
\begin_inset Formula $R_{*}\approx0.145\,\mathrm{R_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 from the VLTI measurement by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citealt{segransan:2003}
\end_layout

\end_inset

), the rotational velocity of LHS\InsetSpace ~
49 is estimated as 
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i=2\pi R_{*}/P\approx0.1\,\kmps$
\end_inset

; negligibly small.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The width of the cross-correlation curves (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\mathrm{CCF}}$
\end_inset

) are calibrated with the rotational velocities (
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i$
\end_inset

) by cross correlating the template spectra against the same template spectra
 with added rotation (convolved with a given 
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i$
\end_inset

), as done by e.g.\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{tinney:1998}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{mohanty:2003}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{white:2003}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A linear limb-darkening law with a solar-like parameter (
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon=0.6$
\end_inset

) was assumed in the formulation of the rotational profile described by
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{gray:1992}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, his Eq.\InsetSpace ~
17.12.
 For each object, two measurements of rotational velocities are computed
 from two independent spectra obtained at different epochs.
 As for the RV measurements, the mean and the standard deviation of the
 mean are used as the final rotational velocity and its uncertainty.
 The final results are recorded in Table\InsetSpace ~

\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{tab:summary_results}

