\begin_layout Standard
We have presented two-epoch RV survey of 18 young BDs and VLM stars (
\begin_inset Formula $0.02~M_{\sun}<M_{*}<0.1~M_{\sun}$
\end_inset

) in UScoOB and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
Oph dark cloud core using the high resolution UVES echelle spectroscopy
 at VLT.
 The average time separation of RV measurements are 21.6\InsetSpace ~
d, and our RV survey
 is sensitive to binaries with separation smaller than 0.1\InsetSpace ~
au.
 One of our targets, USco\InsetSpace ~
121, is most likely a non-member of the UScoOB
 association based on the deviation of the RV from the result of the population
 in the association.
 A similar conclusion was found by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{muzerolle:2003}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from their RV study and the low lithium abundance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found 4 (GY\InsetSpace ~
141, GY\InsetSpace ~
310, USco\InsetSpace ~
55 and USco\InsetSpace ~
104) out of 17 objects as our binary/mu
ltiple candidates.
 This corresponds to the binary fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $24_{-13}^{+16}$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
per\InsetSpace ~
cent for the binary separation 
\begin_inset Formula $a<0.1$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
au.
 We found that the estimated binary fraction is very sensitive to the assumed
 size of systematic error.
 If an additional systematic error of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2\,\kmps$
\end_inset

 is added to the uncertainties in the RV measurements, we find only 2 (GY\InsetSpace ~
310
 and USco\InsetSpace ~
104) out of 17 objects as our binary/multiple candidates, which
 corresponds to the binary fraction of 
\begin_inset Formula $12_{-10}^{+13}$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
per\InsetSpace ~
cent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The recent high-resolution imaging survey of brown dwarfs and very low-mass
 objects (M5.5--M7.5 ) in the UScoOB by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{kraus:2005}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (which was not known to authors at the time of our observation: April--May,
 2004) confirms that USco\InsetSpace ~
55 and USco\InsetSpace ~
66 are multiple systems, and USco\InsetSpace ~
109
 is most likely a multiple system.
 Their projected separations are 
\begin_inset Formula $a>4.0$
\end_inset

\InsetSpace ~
au which is well above our sensitivity limit of 0.1\InsetSpace ~
au; therefore, it is not
 surprising that we did not identify USco\InsetSpace ~
66 and USco\InsetSpace ~
109 as multiples.
 Interestingly, we also found USco\InsetSpace ~
55 as a candidate for a multiple system.
 This may indicate that USco\InsetSpace ~
55 is a triple system with one of object located
 within 0.1\InsetSpace ~
au from the primary.
 In addition, we identify USco\InsetSpace ~
104 as a binary candidate, but this was not
 in their target list.
 Further they found USco\InsetSpace ~
67, 75, 112, 128, 130, 132 as non-multiple, and
 similarly we found them as 'non-candidates' for multiplicity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found the RV dispersion (
\begin_inset Formula $1.2\,\kmps$
\end_inset

) of the objects in UScoOB is very similar to that of the BDs and VLM stars
 in Chamaeleon\InsetSpace ~
I (Cha\InsetSpace ~
I) previous study by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{joergens:2006b}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The rotational velocities (
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i$
\end_inset

) of the samples were also measured.
 The distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i$
\end_inset

 for the UScoOB objects peaks around 
\begin_inset Formula $16.9\,\kmps$
\end_inset

 which is also similar to that of the Cha\InsetSpace ~
I population found by 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Standard


\backslash
citet{joergens:2006b}
\end_layout

\end_inset

; however, the dispersion of 
\begin_inset Formula $v\,\sin i$
\end_inset

 for the UScoOB objects (
\begin_inset Formula $27.8\,\kmps$
\end_inset

) is found to be much larger than that of the Cha\InsetSpace ~
I objects (
\begin_inset Formula $8.0\,\kmps$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

